4 SYNOPSIS:
5 Under existing law, the Board of Trustees of the
6 Department of Archives and History is composed of two
7 members from each congressional district and two
8 at-large members.
9 This bill would increase the composition of the
10 board to 17 members and revise the manner in which
11 members are appointed.
12 This bill would provide for retroactive effect.
13 This bill would also make nonsubstantive,
14 technical revisions to update the existing code
15 language to current style.
16
17
18 A BILL
19 TO BE ENTITLED
20 AN ACT
21
22 Relating to the Department of Archives and History; to
23 amend Sections 41-6-3 and 41-6-4, Code of Alabama 1975; to
24 further provide for the composition of the Board of Trustees
25 of the Department of Archives and History; to further provide
26 for the filling of vacancies on the board; and to provide for
27 retroactive effect.
28 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
Page 1

BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATURE OF ALABAMA:
HB169 INTRODUCED
29 Section 1. Sections 41-6-3 and 41-6-4, Code of Alabama
30 1975, are amended to read as follows:
31 "§41-6-3
32 (a) The department shall be under the control of the
33 Board of Trustees of the Department of Archives and History,
34 which shall consist of one member from each congressional
35 district and the additional members selected pursuant to
36 subsection (b)as the districts existed on January 1, 2025,
37 nine at-large members, and the Governor or his or her
38 designee.
39 (b) Two additional at-large members shall be selected
40 and an additional member shall be selected from each U.S.
41 Congressional District. The additional members shall be
42 selected by the board of trustees and their names shall be
43 communicated to the Senate not later than the fifth
44 legislative day of the 2004 Regular Session of the
45 Legislature. Newly selected members shall be confirmed by the
46 Senate in the same manner as vacancies filled pursuant to
47 Section 41-6-4. The board of trustees shall select three of
48 the new members to serve initial terms of two years, three of
49 the new members to serve initial terms of four years, and
50 three of the new members to serve initial terms of six years.
51 All successor members shall serve terms of six years and shall
52 be selected as provided in Section 41-6-4.
53 (b) Each vacancy in an appointed board seat, as the
54 vacancy arises, whether by expiration of term of service or by
55 death, resignation, or removal shall be filled as follows:
